T1  - TOUGH LOVE AND INTERGENERATIONAL ALTRUISM*
AU  - Bhatt, Vipul
AU  - Ogaki, Masao
Y1  - 2012/08/01
PY  - 2012
DA  - 2012/08/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-2354.2012.00701.x
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
SP  - 791
EP  - 814
VL  - 53
IS  - 3
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-2354.2012.00701.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - This article develops and studies a tough love model of intergenerational altruism. We model tough love by modifying the Barro-Becker standard altruism model in two ways. First, the child?s discount factor is endogenously determined, so lower childhood consumption leads to a higher discount factor later in life. Second, the parent evaluates the child?s lifetime utility with a constant high discount factor. Our model predicts that parental transfers will fall when the child?s discount factor falls. This is in contrast with the standard altruism model, which predicts that parental transfers are independent of exogenous changes in the child?s discount factor.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - MODEL UNCERTAINTY AND EXCHANGE RATE VOLATILITY*
AU  - Markiewicz, Agnieszka
Y1  - 2012/08/01
PY  - 2012
DA  - 2012/08/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-2354.2012.00702.x
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
SP  - 815
EP  - 844
VL  - 53
IS  - 3
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-2354.2012.00702.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - This article proposes an explanation for shifts in the volatility of exchange-rate returns. Agents are uncertain about the true data generating model and deal with this uncertainty by making inference on the models and their parameters' approach, I call model learning. Model learning may lead agents to focus excessively on a subset of fundamental variables. Consequently, exchange-rate volatility is determined by the dynamics of these fundamentals and changes as agents alter models. I investigate the empirical relevance of model learning and find that the change in volatility of GBP/USD in 1993 was triggered by a shift between models.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - EX ANTE INVESTMENT, EX POST REMEDIES, AND PRODUCT LIABILITY*
AU  - Chen, Yongmin
AU  - Hua, Xinyu
Y1  - 2012/08/01
PY  - 2012
DA  - 2012/08/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-2354.2012.00703.x
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
SP  - 845
EP  - 866
VL  - 53
IS  - 3
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-2354.2012.00703.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - A firm can increase product safety through ex ante investment and can remedy quality problems after sales. An increase in product liability raises returns to ex ante investment through higher consumer demand, but may also negatively affect the investment incentive due to more ex post remedial activities. The trade-off between these ?output? and ?substitution? effects can result in an inverted U-shaped relationship between product liability and ex ante investment. We find that the firm prefers full liability, but consumer surplus can be higher under partial liability. We further identify conditions under which full liability or partial liability is socially optimal.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - FORECASTING INFLATION USING DYNAMIC MODEL AVERAGING*
AU  - Koop, Gary
AU  - Korobilis, Dimitris
Y1  - 2012/08/01
PY  - 2012
DA  - 2012/08/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-2354.2012.00704.x
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
SP  - 867
EP  - 886
VL  - 53
IS  - 3
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-2354.2012.00704.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - We forecast quarterly US inflation based on the generalized Phillips curve using econometric methods that incorporate dynamic model averaging. These methods not only allow for coefficients to change over time, but also allow for the entire forecasting model to change over time. We find that dynamic model averaging leads to substantial forecasting improvements over simple benchmark regressions and more sophisticated approaches such as those using time varying coefficient models. We also provide evidence on which sets of predictors are relevant for forecasting in each period.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - ON ASYMPTOTIC PROPERTIES OF THE PARAMETERS OF DIFFERENTIATED PRODUCT DEMAND AND SUPPLY SYSTEMS WHEN DEMOGRAPHICALLY CATEGORIZED PURCHASING PATTERN DATA ARE AVAILABLE*
